it over to our speaker for today's meetup, Paul Chang. Hey, Paul. Hey, great. Thanks, Rachel.

00:02:06.639 --> 00:02:15.839
Thanks, Tom. And thanks, everybody, for joining in in this presentation. So yesterday, I will

00:02:15.839 --> 00:02:22.639
be talking about capacity planning for Azure data centers. And this is a joint work with

00:02:23.440 --> 00:02:32.559
our fantastic team, Sarah, Ivy, Yajun, Ritchie, Sajay, and Serge. But this is also

00:02:32.559 --> 00:02:41.520
joint work with our former team members as well. So Amit, who's at Airbnb, and also Jingyi

00:02:41.520 --> 00:02:49.919
and Yantao, who have moved on to different roles in Microsoft. Okay, so the agenda for

00:02:49.919 --> 00:02:58.559
this presentation. So I will describe the capacity planning process for Azure data centers. I'll then

00:02:58.559 --> 00:03:07.199
describe how we use RStudio Connect to generate these capacity plans, the value that we get from

00:03:07.199 --> 00:03:15.759
RStudio Connect. And then I'll do a demo involving a simplified version of a Shiny dashboard

00:03:16.320 --> 00:03:25.440
that we built. Okay, so before we get into the planning process, let's get to know

00:03:25.440 --> 00:03:35.440
Azure a little bit. So Azure is Microsoft's cloud platform. We have 200 products and cloud services.

00:03:36.240 --> 00:03:44.240
We serve over a billion customers worldwide. 20 million companies are on Azure.

00:03:45.199 --> 00:03:55.119
And we're in 60 plus regions around the world. We have over 90 regulatory compliance offerings,

00:03:55.839 --> 00:04:03.360
the most of any cloud provider. 95% of Fortune 500 companies are on Azure.

00:04:04.240 --> 00:04:11.839
And Microsoft spends a billion dollars in cybersecurity every year. So Microsoft is

00:04:11.839 --> 00:04:21.040
very, very passionate about data security, data privacy. Now, in order to enable these

00:04:21.040 --> 00:04:30.160
cloud services, we have built a global infrastructure that consists of 165,000 miles

00:04:30.160 --> 00:04:39.279
of fiber optic cable, over 200 data centers, and a lot of land, a lot of land.

00:04:41.679 --> 00:04:50.239
Key features of our Azure data centers, high availability, low latency, so super important

00:04:50.239 --> 00:05:02.239
for gamers, scalability. And by using Azure, we ensure that our customers have access to the

00:05:02.239 --> 00:05:12.799
latest cloud technologies. Your data is safe and secure. So if you architect your workload in a

00:05:12.799 --> 00:05:20.079
certain way, where your workload consists of multiple Azure services, those Azure services

00:05:20.079 --> 00:05:27.359
can communicate with one another over the Microsoft network. So that IP traffic never

00:05:27.359 --> 00:05:36.959
enters the public internet, and so your data stays safe and secure. Okay, so now let's talk about

00:05:36.959 --> 00:05:44.799
capacity planning a little bit. So we are a group of economists, data scientists, and we work with

00:05:44.799 --> 00:05:53.600
this fantastic group of program managers to produce the long-range capacity plan for Azure data

00:05:53.600 --> 00:06:01.920
centers. Now, some characteristics of our plan. So we do look at the 127-year time horizon,

00:06:02.640 --> 00:06:10.799
and the data center build-out process is characterized by somewhat long lead times.

00:06:11.600 --> 00:06:19.440
So typically, roughly around the two-year mark, but in certain instances, that lead time could be a

00:06:19.440 --> 00:06:27.839
lot longer than two years. We invest billions of dollars in our data centers and our global

00:06:27.839 --> 00:06:35.760
infrastructure, and our capacity plan is for the 60-plus regions that we are in right now,

00:06:36.640 --> 00:06:42.640
and with the hope of expanding into a lot more regions in the coming years.

00:06:44.320 --> 00:06:54.160
Okay, in terms of our workflow summary, these are roughly the main entities that we interact with.

00:06:54.720 --> 00:07:01.519
So note that this diagram is not necessarily reflective of our internal organizational

00:07:01.519 --> 00:07:08.799
structure, but I think this captures the salient features of our workflow. So we're capacity

00:07:08.799 --> 00:07:17.600
planning in the center there. We ingest data from hardware and region design. We ingest demand from

00:07:17.600 --> 00:07:25.119
various partners to generate our demand forecast models and our capacity plans.

00:07:25.920 --> 00:07:33.600
We also collaborate closely with finance to iterate on the capacity plans, and we also

00:07:33.600 --> 00:07:40.320
collaborate with our supply team closely as well. So we give demand signals to our supply team.

00:07:40.320 --> 00:07:49.519
They, in turn, do the hard work of figuring out where the supply is, where the most cost-effective

00:07:49.519 --> 00:07:58.880
supply is, and they give that information back to us, which in turn affects or influences where we

00:07:58.880 --> 00:08:08.959
shape demand. Okay, so now let's double-click on demand bucket first. So here are some main

00:08:08.959 --> 00:08:15.200
categories of demand inputs that we consider. There's this bucket that we call organic data,

00:08:15.200 --> 00:08:22.799
so it consists of economic data and historical Azure revenue that we use to feed into our

00:08:22.799 --> 00:08:31.519
econometric and data science models. On top of that, we do consider capacity requests from

00:08:31.519 --> 00:08:40.080
various Microsoft engineering groups, being Office 365, Xbox. As well, we also consider

00:08:41.359 --> 00:08:48.400
capacity requests from our large customers. So we actually have a large team of people who talk with

00:08:48.400 --> 00:08:56.719
governments and large enterprises, you know, Fortune 500 companies, and these customers,

00:08:56.719 --> 00:09:05.440
when they onboard onto Azure or they make a new capacity request, those capacity asks are actually

00:09:05.440 --> 00:09:12.960
pretty large usually. And so those type of large capacity requests are not necessarily forecastable

00:09:13.760 --> 00:09:22.000
by the historical data. So for that reason, we really need to consider demand from large

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:30.239
customers as a separate bucket. Okay, in terms of hardware and region design,

00:09:30.880 --> 00:09:39.119
so Azure services, right, so various Azure services actually depend on core Azure services.

00:09:40.320 --> 00:09:45.760
Some Azure services have special server requirements, special hardware requirements,

00:09:45.760 --> 00:09:51.840
so we need to take account of those considerations. The hardware roadmap,

00:09:51.840 --> 00:10:00.320
that's another big input for us. So yeah, I don't know if Moore's Law is still valid or not,

00:10:01.280 --> 00:10:11.119
but I think it is still our thinking that as time goes on, CPUs should become more powerful and

00:10:11.840 --> 00:10:17.039
energy efficient. And so if CPUs and GPUs, they get better and better,

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:25.359
the thinking is perhaps we might need fewer servers and maybe even fewer buildings to serve

00:10:25.359 --> 00:10:35.119
the same demand. Supply, so we build data centers, we lease data centers, and as I said before,

00:10:35.119 --> 00:10:45.039
we want to know where the supply is around the world. Okay, so we ingest all that information

00:10:45.039 --> 00:10:56.320
from our partners to produce the capacity plan. These are roughly four of the main pillars

00:10:56.320 --> 00:11:04.400
that support our work, that allow us to produce the capacity plan. So the first is revenue forecasts.

00:11:05.119 --> 00:11:13.280
So we have a revenue forecast model that employs a couple of well-understood models that we stitch

00:11:13.280 --> 00:11:21.039
together, including a model on technology diffusion inspired by Diego Coleman. We have a

00:11:21.039 --> 00:11:28.880
hierarchical time series model that allows us to distribute a worldwide revenue forecast down to

00:11:28.880 --> 00:11:38.239
the geo and region level. We have a gravity model of trade. The hardware roadmap is another big

00:11:38.239 --> 00:11:48.320
pillar that our team works on. So, I mean, Microsoft does have an internal hardware roadmap, but

00:11:50.320 --> 00:11:57.840
it's not necessarily written in stone, right? So all sorts of things could pop up and that plan

00:11:57.840 --> 00:12:05.919
may need to be changed from time to time. So we do want to actually forecast that hardware

00:12:05.919 --> 00:12:13.280
roadmap as well, to the extent that we can. Capacity principles are also important, right? So

00:12:13.280 --> 00:12:20.159
we need to account for the discrete sizes of various data centers due to their design, and we

00:12:20.159 --> 00:12:28.400
also need to build in safety stock to account for supply lead time and volatility on both the supply

00:12:28.400 --> 00:12:39.039
and demand sides. And the fourth is demand shaping, which I'll talk more about in the demo later in

00:12:39.039 --> 00:12:47.760
this presentation. Okay, so that hopefully gives people a good overview of what we do, what's our

00:12:47.760 --> 00:12:57.440
process. So to summarize, the demand info we use for our models comes from historical revenue

00:12:59.280 --> 00:13:06.320
and sales data, as well as capacity requests from large customers and Microsoft engineering groups.

00:13:07.200 --> 00:13:13.359
You need to account for hardware and region design requirements, including special or premium

00:13:13.359 --> 00:13:20.239
hardware needed for various Microsoft engineering groups. Supply, so we need to be aware of the

00:13:20.239 --> 00:13:28.559
places where we have plenty of supply and where we don't. In certain cases, we want to lease data

00:13:28.559 --> 00:13:34.320
centers because of the lower lead time, and in other cases, we want to build data centers to have

00:13:34.320 --> 00:13:43.520
more control and maybe lower costs. And in all we do, we want to be fiscally responsible.

00:13:44.159 --> 00:13:57.359
So that's very important. Okay, so for our team, what are the top considerations for our team

00:13:58.159 --> 00:14:08.799
for doing this capacity planning? I think the close to the top one is accuracy, right?

00:14:10.479 --> 00:14:15.840
So like many other data science teams, we care very much about accuracy.

00:14:17.280 --> 00:14:22.400
It's how we build credibility, super important that our models are accurate.

00:14:23.119 --> 00:14:31.200
But that's not the only consideration that we need in order for our team to be successful.

00:14:31.919 --> 00:14:39.200
So I think data science teams and models, they tend to over-index on accuracy,

00:14:39.760 --> 00:14:47.200
but in order to make our models a success, we need other factors as well. So the other

00:14:47.919 --> 00:14:56.320
big considerations are timeliness, right? So we need to produce capacity plans on time,

00:14:56.880 --> 00:15:06.960
every month. Delays in publishing this plan can be costly, right? So we don't get new capacity

00:15:06.960 --> 00:15:12.880
unless it is signaled in this plan. And if we don't get new capacity in a timely manner,

00:15:13.760 --> 00:15:20.080
there's a risk of lost demand and other delays. So it's very important for us that we produce

00:15:20.080 --> 00:15:30.479
plans on time consistently. Business strategy, so we need to be agile to incorporate new ideas,

00:15:30.479 --> 00:15:38.159
thoughts, intelligence from our stakeholders and leaders. So we need to override inputs in case

00:15:38.159 --> 00:15:44.719
new information comes in, or if there are occasionally data quality issues with some

00:15:44.719 --> 00:15:52.000
of our input data. So if we do detect data quality issues, we need to be able to override

00:15:54.159 --> 00:16:02.239
those inputs in a non-hacky way, in a robust non-hacky way. And the last one, I think in some

00:16:02.320 --> 00:16:11.679
ways this might be the most important consideration, explainability. So we gain

00:16:11.679 --> 00:16:20.799
trust only when we can explain the drivers behind the capacity plan in a clear and concise manner.

00:16:22.640 --> 00:16:29.520
Shiny apps help a lot with this, by the way. So we love shiny apps, we love shiny dashboards.

00:16:30.320 --> 00:16:41.440
I think it's only when our explanations are clear and concise that we are able to also be

00:16:41.440 --> 00:16:48.239
transparent with our internal stakeholders and partners. So I really think explainability is

00:16:48.239 --> 00:16:58.159
one of these key things that you need that enables us to be transparent. And when we are able to be

00:16:58.159 --> 00:17:04.719
transparent and open with our partners about our model assumptions, about the input data that we

00:17:04.719 --> 00:17:12.800
see, then we start building trust. So being transparent, that enables us to build trust

00:17:12.800 --> 00:17:23.599
with our stakeholders. And that trust, it leads to more questions. So being able to build that trust

00:17:24.160 --> 00:17:28.000
leads to us having good conversations with our internal stakeholders,

00:17:29.359 --> 00:17:36.400
and that leads to more collaboration. So I think this entire chain of goodness that starts from

00:17:37.040 --> 00:17:45.119
being explainable. Explainability leads to transparency, leads to trust, leads to

00:17:45.119 --> 00:17:52.479
collaboration. So I think this is a big one for me. I'm very passionate about explainability.

00:17:54.000 --> 00:18:03.520
Okay, so with that said, let me talk about how we use RStudio Connect to help us

00:18:04.959 --> 00:18:07.760
address these considerations and help us do our work.

00:18:10.800 --> 00:18:20.880
Okay, so let me paint a picture of our work life before adopting RStudio Connect.

00:18:20.880 --> 00:18:31.839
So truthfully, it wasn't bad. It wasn't bad at all. It was not that great either,

00:18:31.839 --> 00:18:41.599
but it wasn't that bad. So before using RStudio Connect, models were developed by

00:18:41.599 --> 00:18:47.839
data scientists using R and C Sharp, and the data scientists would check that code in.

00:18:48.479 --> 00:18:55.680
And they would be deployed by engineers in data pipelines using Databricks. It's important to

00:18:55.680 --> 00:19:02.000
note that most of our data is mid-sized. So we typically deal with data that's, you know,

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:09.280
at most maybe 100 gigabytes roughly, right? So our team doesn't really deal with petabytes of data.

00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:16.880
Other teams deal with petabytes. We don't directly deal with big data.

00:19:17.920 --> 00:19:24.560
And so the pipelines would run in Databricks. It would take an hour for the pipeline to run.

00:19:24.560 --> 00:19:31.119
It would dump the data in some database, and then people would sort of extract that data

00:19:32.400 --> 00:19:40.160
and, you know, create static tables, static graphs, and paste them in PowerPoint presentations.

00:19:41.040 --> 00:19:44.880
And then they would present these presentations with our stakeholders.

00:19:45.680 --> 00:19:53.280
Our stakeholders would have feedback for us, and then our data scientists would have to

00:19:53.280 --> 00:20:00.079
either create new models or modify existing models, and then the cycle would continue.

00:20:01.119 --> 00:20:07.520
So what were the pain points before we started using RStudio Connect?

00:20:08.160 --> 00:20:15.359
I think the big one for me was just slow. It was just slow, slow, slow.

00:20:16.400 --> 00:20:20.880
Slow end-to-end development time, right? So that cycle that I just talked about,

00:20:20.880 --> 00:20:26.719
you know, was like a couple days between when the data scientists would modify some

00:20:28.959 --> 00:20:35.520
model to stakeholder feedback. And remember, we have to publish this capacity plan

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:43.040
on a monthly basis, right? There's 20 working days in a month, so three days is a long

00:20:43.040 --> 00:20:53.040
time within that 20-day time span. So Databricks is great for big data,

00:20:53.040 --> 00:20:59.839
right? So Databricks and also Azure Synapse, these are actually really great platforms for

00:21:00.640 --> 00:21:07.920
dealing with big data, from getting insights from big data. But for our case, where we're

00:21:07.920 --> 00:21:13.280
only working with a couple hundred gigabytes of data, it's actually a lot faster for us to run

00:21:14.479 --> 00:21:21.920
our models on a laptop or on a desktop machine, right? So it's really, for our case,

00:21:22.479 --> 00:21:26.800
it should not take an hour for the pipeline to run end-to-end.

00:21:28.079 --> 00:21:32.800
Now, having said that, even in the current workflow, we still depend on big data.

00:21:33.680 --> 00:21:39.119
I think some of our upstream teams, they probably use some of these big data platforms to produce

00:21:39.119 --> 00:21:46.319
our input data. So I still think Databricks is great. I think Azure Synapse is great. But for

00:21:46.319 --> 00:21:54.160
our particular scenario, it was, you know, we could get things done faster using something else.

00:21:55.520 --> 00:22:00.880
Hard to do what-if scenarios. So if somebody wanted to change an input parameter from

00:22:00.880 --> 00:22:06.160
one to two, you know, yeah, sure, change the input parameter one to two,

00:22:07.280 --> 00:22:15.040
hit enter, and it'd take an hour for the results to come out. So that big lag between

00:22:15.040 --> 00:22:20.479
changing an input and getting model results, you know, that makes it hard to do what-if scenarios.

00:22:21.439 --> 00:22:29.439
And then visualization of results. So I will say that, you know, during this time period before

00:22:29.439 --> 00:22:36.880
we onboarded to RStudio Connect, our data scientists were already experimenting with

00:22:37.680 --> 00:22:43.599
creating R Shiny apps, right? So we were already testing that out. We were also,

00:22:44.160 --> 00:22:51.920
we were already sort of using it internally in our team. But there was a big requirement,

00:22:51.920 --> 00:22:58.319
right? There was a big desire for us to be able to share those Shiny apps with our internal

00:22:58.319 --> 00:23:04.319
partners and stakeholders, right? So at that time, we didn't have a means of deploying Shiny apps.

00:23:04.959 --> 00:23:15.199
And so I think it was really that need to be able to deploy Shiny apps that prompted us to

00:23:15.199 --> 00:23:22.719
explore options, right? And so I think the great option that we landed on was RStudio Connect.

00:23:24.160 --> 00:23:32.079
So before I get to this slide, a big shout out to Amit Gandhi, who is no longer with

00:23:32.640 --> 00:23:39.040
our team. He's over in Airbnb. I think he's, I think he looked at this situation before,

00:23:39.920 --> 00:23:46.000
and he was really instrumental, really, really instrumental in driving our team

00:23:46.000 --> 00:23:54.319
to adopt RStudio Connect. So I think he's, I think he's the single person most responsible

00:23:54.640 --> 00:23:59.280
for sort of shifting our team towards this new model of development.

00:24:00.319 --> 00:24:08.800
So after we adopted RStudio Connect, what is the model for how we work? In this new world,

00:24:08.800 --> 00:24:15.520
data scientists own the entire model development lifecycle. So data scientists write the data

00:24:15.520 --> 00:24:21.280
ingestion jobs, they develop the models, they deploy models on RStudio Connect,

00:24:22.079 --> 00:24:30.319
and they write Shiny apps to visualize results. We also use some R Markdown documents as well.

00:24:31.760 --> 00:24:38.719
At the same time, our engineers remain vital, indispensable. The engineers,

00:24:39.839 --> 00:24:46.319
we could not do our work without engineers. They are responsible for creating and maintaining the

00:24:46.319 --> 00:24:53.439
infrastructure for running RStudio Connect and other Azure services. They are responsible for

00:24:53.439 --> 00:25:03.199
creating the architecture. They also help shepherd the R packages that data scientists write.

00:25:03.920 --> 00:25:10.719
So there are questions about data contracts, how can we ensure the data scientists work seamlessly

00:25:10.719 --> 00:25:16.800
with each other, but also with other teams throughout Microsoft. So engineers have a big

00:25:16.800 --> 00:25:26.319
part in that design work, data compliance and security. Of course, big topics, big areas of

00:25:26.319 --> 00:25:38.479
responsibility for the engineers. Advantages. So as I said before, RStudio Connect empowers our data

00:25:38.479 --> 00:25:46.239
scientists to directly communicate insights to stakeholders. They own the development lifecycle

00:25:46.239 --> 00:25:54.640
end-to-end. The end-to-end development time is now quick, right? It can be as little as a couple

00:25:54.640 --> 00:26:03.199
hours between model development to deploying the app on RStudio Connect to getting stakeholder

00:26:03.199 --> 00:26:09.839
feedback. Easy collaboration between the data scientists. So we love the pins package, by the

00:26:09.839 --> 00:26:19.280
way. So we share data sets amongst ourselves using pins. We write most of our code in R packages,

00:26:19.280 --> 00:26:27.760
and we can share code between ourselves via R packages easily. And now it's easy to do

00:26:27.760 --> 00:26:36.719
what-if scenarios, right? So we're able to deploy Plumber APIs, and we're able to write shiny apps

00:26:36.719 --> 00:26:46.800
that talk to those Plumber APIs. And so in doing so, we're able to create dynamic apps, right, where

00:26:46.800 --> 00:26:55.040
people can fiddle around with input parameters and do sensitivity analyses in essentially real time,

00:26:55.040 --> 00:27:01.760
right? So it no longer takes an hour for people to explore, you know, what happens

00:27:01.760 --> 00:27:07.760
if I change this parameter or that parameter. It's now real time, right, due to this combination

00:27:07.760 --> 00:27:20.000
of shiny apps and Plumber APIs. So the return on investment on RStudio Connect is clear to us.

00:27:20.800 --> 00:27:28.560
So we have been consistently on time and publishing the capacity plan every month. No

00:27:28.560 --> 00:27:37.599
delays. As I said before, any delays are, they're potentially costly. So really being on time,

00:27:37.599 --> 00:27:48.479
that's huge. Transparency and explainability. So I'm a big fan of shiny apps, shiny dashboards.

00:27:49.199 --> 00:27:53.439
It's super quick to put together a dashboard and deploy it on RStudio Connect.

00:27:54.560 --> 00:28:01.839
And even if some of the algorithms we develop are black boxes, if people can interact with

00:28:01.839 --> 00:28:09.599
the models via the shiny apps, and if it kind of looks right, then that capability alone is

00:28:09.599 --> 00:28:15.839
powerful, right? So sometimes it's really hard to sort of explain the guts of an algorithm.

00:28:16.400 --> 00:28:21.920
If it, on the other hand, if it kind of looks right, if it performs as people expect it,

00:28:22.560 --> 00:28:28.000
you know, in a lot of cases, that alone might be sufficient, right? That alone might go a long

00:28:28.000 --> 00:28:34.479
way towards explainability and building that trust that I talked about. And finally, I think

00:28:34.479 --> 00:28:41.199
our data scientists are just happier. I think they're just happier with this new world.

