00:31:38.000 --> 00:31:46.079
internal customers use. Okay, so before I get to the demo itself, let me give a brief introduction

00:31:46.079 --> 00:31:56.800
to availability zones. So availability zones are physically and logically separated data centers

00:31:56.800 --> 00:32:07.520
with their own independent power source and pooling. Okay, so the basic idea is that if

00:32:07.520 --> 00:32:13.520
one of these zones go down, right, perhaps due to some natural disaster or,

00:32:15.920 --> 00:32:23.599
you know, or maybe somebody accidentally hits the power off switch. So if any of these things

00:32:23.599 --> 00:32:31.599
happen, then those workloads can fill over to another availability zone, and that workload

00:32:31.599 --> 00:32:40.719
can continue to function. So it's this fill over capability that gives our customers workloads that

00:32:40.719 --> 00:32:48.000
high availability, right? It's how we can guarantee these high SLAs for our customers.

00:32:49.040 --> 00:32:58.079
Now, in terms of demand, we actually think of a demand as split into three buckets. So there is a

00:32:58.079 --> 00:33:05.439
portion of demand that we think of as being pinned to a particular zone. So this workload must

00:33:06.560 --> 00:33:12.560
happen in this physical location, right? So there is that type of demand. There's a second class

00:33:12.560 --> 00:33:17.359
of demand where it's just, you know, it just has to be replicated across all three zones,

00:33:18.560 --> 00:33:25.119
mainly for that resiliency that I was talking about. And the last type of demand is this

00:33:26.079 --> 00:33:33.760
discretionary demand. So there's this third type of demand where we are basically free to

00:33:33.760 --> 00:33:43.599
allocate that demand into any or all of these availability zones as we see fit. Okay, so now,

00:33:44.479 --> 00:33:50.959
so we can place this demand, we can allocate this demand however we want. And so then the question

00:33:51.040 --> 00:33:58.160
is, well, how should we allocate this demand, right? So there are a number of policies that we

00:33:58.160 --> 00:34:07.760
might want to optimize for, right? So one might be we want to allocate demand in such a way that

00:34:08.560 --> 00:34:16.159
we try to maximize and equalize the amount of excess supply that we have in any of the three

00:34:16.159 --> 00:34:22.239
zones, right? So that's perhaps one policy objective. Another policy objective might be

00:34:23.199 --> 00:34:29.600
we want to push demand to zones where we can get the most cost-effective supply,

00:34:30.399 --> 00:34:35.760
right? So, and there could be others as well, right? There are other heuristics, other policy

00:34:35.760 --> 00:34:42.879
decisions or policies that we might want to consider when we're trying to allocate this

00:34:42.879 --> 00:34:51.600
discretionary demand. Okay, so some background on the demo that you're about to see. So I have

00:34:51.600 --> 00:35:01.520
implemented a new algorithm for distributing this discretionary demand. I spent hours debugging

00:35:03.120 --> 00:35:11.919
the code and debugging the code and debugging the code. And at the end of that, I was finally able

00:35:11.919 --> 00:35:20.159
to create a first version of the capacity plan with this new algorithm. And so I shared the

00:35:20.159 --> 00:35:30.879
results with our program managers and other partners. And the feedback was, you know,

00:35:30.879 --> 00:35:35.360
there was some feedback that said, hey, look, this doesn't look right, right? This result doesn't

00:35:35.360 --> 00:35:40.399
look right. And so there are some genuine bugs that were found. And so I went and fixed those bugs.

00:35:41.199 --> 00:35:47.520
But there was other feedback that was like, hey, you know, I'm not quite sure what the algorithm

00:35:47.520 --> 00:35:53.760
is doing in this particular region. I would get questions like, hey, can you actually explain what

00:35:53.760 --> 00:36:02.560
this algorithm is actually doing? I'm not quite sure I understand, right? And so it was apparent

00:36:02.560 --> 00:36:08.959
to me after getting that feedback that I really, really needed some type of visualization to build

00:36:08.959 --> 00:36:15.199
trust in the algorithm that I just developed, right? To give people a sense of what the algorithm

00:36:15.199 --> 00:36:26.000
was doing without actually having to delve too deep into the details. So given that,

00:36:26.000 --> 00:36:32.159
I spent a couple hours putting together an interactive demo that would allow people to

00:36:32.159 --> 00:36:39.280
adjust some model parameters and to get a feel for the algorithm, right? And so if people can

00:36:39.280 --> 00:36:46.080
even just get a feel for the algorithm, then I think that would build trust and confidence in

00:36:46.080 --> 00:36:52.879
the algorithm, even if I don't delve too deeply into the nitty-gritty details of the algorithm.

