01:01:34.959 --> 01:01:42.080
reason why it's faster for us to sort of run the models on our local machines, right? If anything

01:01:42.080 --> 01:01:48.479
takes days, we're back to Azure Synapse, right? Then we're not running these things on our local

01:01:48.479 --> 01:01:58.000
machines anymore. Thanks, Paul. Someone asked, are you all using linear programming to do these zone

01:01:58.000 --> 01:02:07.600
modeling functions for the discretionary demand piece? The short answer is no. I actually think

01:02:07.600 --> 01:02:13.280
that in my, so I've actually worked on a couple other projects where, you know, these types of

01:02:13.280 --> 01:02:18.479
constraint satisfaction problems where, you know, you're trying to allocate demand or allocate,

01:02:19.040 --> 01:02:25.760
you know, number of seats or whatever in some problem. I've actually, to be honest with you,

01:02:25.760 --> 01:02:32.639
I've actually never used linear programming in practice myself. I've often used these types of

01:02:33.199 --> 01:02:39.840
quote-unquote traditional AI techniques to try to do the optimization. In this particular case,

01:02:39.840 --> 01:02:44.000
it's actually simpler than that. We just, there was just a bunch of heuristics that we employed

01:02:44.000 --> 01:02:49.120
in the algorithm. And so, I'm pretty sure that the heuristics that we employed are not

01:02:49.919 --> 01:02:57.040
necessarily optimal. There is a case to be made to sort of balance between optimality

01:02:57.040 --> 01:03:02.080
and explainability, by the way, right? So, if you try to optimize your algorithm too much,

01:03:02.080 --> 01:03:07.840
you have a, in general, you might have a harder time explaining. So, the short answer is no,

01:03:07.840 --> 01:03:14.080
we don't use linear programming. Thanks, Paul. There was another question about the dashboard

